<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>be out of the woods • take to the woods</xh5><p> <i>be out of the woods</i>—(often negat.) be finally free from trouble or difficulties <i>(also: be out of the wood): </i>The Prime Minister is by no means <u>out of the woods</u>, and must fight to defend his leadership.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>come out of the woodwork</b>—appear as though out of nowhere, especially in large numbers: He won the lottery and has had old “friends” and distant relatives <u>coming out of the woodwork</u> ever since.</p><p><i>take to the woods</i>—run away from one’s responsibilities; get away from trouble and hide: When trouble comes, wise men take to their work; weak men <u>take to the woods</u>.</p> </entry>
